 Let x represent the number of lunks needed to purchase a dozen apples. Since $2$ kunks can buy $4$ apples, $1$ kunk can buy $2$ apples. Therefore, $12$ kunks can buy $24$ apples, and $x$ lunks can also buy $24$ apples. We can set up the proportion
\begin{align*} \frac{x\text{ lunks}}{24 \text{ lunks}} &= \frac{5 \text{ lunks}}{3 \text{ kunks}}\cdot \frac{2 \text{ kunks}}{4 \text{ apples}}\cdot \frac{24 \text{ apples}}{1 \text{ kunk}}. \end{align*}
Multiplying by the reciprocal on both sides of the equation, we find that $x=20$. </think> <answer> $\textbf{(C)}$ 20 </answer>

